   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Mean Functions\n",
    "\n",
    "In the previous chapter we talked about [kernels](kernels.html). If you go back and look at the plots, you may notice that even in the plots without any data, where we just look at $f$ samples, the $f$ samples are kind of close to 0. Why is that? The kernels define what kinds of shape $f$ can take, but not where the function is; a mean function defines where. In the section on kernels we didn't specify a mean function, and the default mean function is constant 0, which explains why, by default, $f$ samples will be close to 0."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "43b80e63",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As usual we will start with some necessary imports:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "8a2b5c77",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:41.251767Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:41.250766Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:44.044960Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:44.044351Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "import tensorflow as tf\n",
    "\n",
    "import gpflow\n",
    "from gpflow.experimental.check_shapes import inherit_check_shapes"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "24f4fcaf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And a helper function to visualise our models:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "6fd5145f",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:44.047314Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:44.047041Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:44.051843Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:44.051353Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def plot_model(\n",
    "    model: gpflow.models.GPModel, *, min_x: float, max_x: float, optimise: bool = True\n",
    ") -> None:\n",
    "    fig, ax = plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=1)\n",
    "\n",
    "    if optimise:\n",
    "        opt = gpflow.optimizers.Scipy()\n",
    "        opt.minimize(\n",
    "            model.training_loss, model.trainable_variables, options=dict(maxiter=1000)\n",
    "        )\n",
    "\n",
    "    Xplot = np.linspace(min_x, max_x, 300)[:, None]\n",
    "\n",
    "    f_mean, f_var = model.predict_f(Xplot, full_cov=False)\n",
    "    f_lower = f_mean - 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "    f_upper = f_mean + 1.96 * np.sqrt(f_var)\n",
    "\n",
    "    ax.hlines(0.0, min_x, max_x, colors=\"black\", linestyles=\"dotted\", alpha=0.3)\n",
    "    ax.scatter(X, Y, color=\"black\")\n",
    "    (mean_line,) = ax.plot(Xplot, f_mean, \"-\")\n",
    "    color = mean_line.get_color()\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xplot, f_lower, \"--\", color=color)\n",
    "    ax.plot(Xplot, f_upper, \"--\", color=color)\n",
    "    ax.fill_between(Xplot[:, 0], f_lower[:, 0], f_upper[:, 0], color=color, alpha=0.1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4198ccd3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Mean reversal\n",
    "\n",
    "Observe:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "6ffe0439",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:44.053754Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:44.053551Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:45.602901Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:45.602369Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "X = np.array([[0.0], [0.1], [0.2], [0.3], [0.4]])\n",
    "Y = np.array([[2.0], [1.7], [1.6], [1.7], [2.0]])\n",
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR((X, Y), kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern32())\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-0.1, max_x=4.1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a09cf98e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "As we move away from the data our predictions converge towards 0. Basically, as we move away from the data, the model does not know what to predict, and will revert towards the mean function. This is called [\"mean reversal](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regression_toward_the_mean), and this is the primary use case where having a reasonable mean function can help. In the areas where we have plenty of data, we don't need a mean function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2da4e79c",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Setting a mean function\n",
    "\n",
    "Our models generally take a `mean_function` parameter that you can set to any instance of [gpflow.functions.MeanFunction](../../api/gpflow/functions/index.html#gpflow.functions.MeanFunction). See our [API documentation](../../api/gpflow/functions/index.html) for a full list of built-in mean functions.\n",
    "\n",
    "In the above example I happen to know that our data is a quadratic function, so let us try setting our mean function to a 2nd degree polynomial:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "d01efc6a",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:45.605138Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:45.604980Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.073504Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.072977Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern32(),\n",
    "    mean_function=gpflow.functions.Polynomial(2),\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-0.1, max_x=4.1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "83791be4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Our model now fits our mean function to the data without any noise, and happily extrapolates the quadtratic function."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "92a1aaaf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Interactions with the kernel\n",
    "\n",
    "The shape of $f$, determined by the kernel, is relative to the mean function.\n",
    "\n",
    "So, if we have a linear mean function:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "86802cd2",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.075613Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.075452Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.449891Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.449359Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "X = np.array([[0.0], [0.1], [0.2], [0.3], [0.4]])\n",
    "Y = np.array([[1.0], [1.3], [1.2], [1.5], [1.4]])\n",
    "\n",
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Constant(),\n",
    "    mean_function=gpflow.functions.Linear(),\n",
    "    noise_variance=1e-3,\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-1.0, max_x=1.4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "b7d0b4a5",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And a periodic kernel:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "9295002d",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.451842Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.451640Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.915863Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.915401Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Periodic(gpflow.kernels.Matern32(), period=0.2),\n",
    "    mean_function=gpflow.functions.Zero(),\n",
    "    noise_variance=1e-3,\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-1.0, max_x=1.4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "a1bd2592",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "And combine them, we get a period around a line:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "cac446ab",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.930592Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:46.930426Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:47.430789Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:47.430321Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Periodic(gpflow.kernels.Matern32(), period=0.2),\n",
    "    mean_function=gpflow.functions.Linear(),\n",
    "    noise_variance=1e-3,\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-1.0, max_x=1.4)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fc2fa9ec",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Custom mean functions\n",
    "\n",
    "It is easy enough to create a custom mean function. You must extend the [gpflow.functions.MeanFunction](../../api/gpflow/functions/index.html#gpflow.functions.MeanFunction) class, which only requires you to implement a `__call__` method. For example:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "1dceb59d",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:47.432825Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:47.432644Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:47.770096Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:47.769523Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "class SineMeanFunction(gpflow.functions.MeanFunction):\n",
    "    @inherit_check_shapes\n",
    "    def __call__(self, X: gpflow.base.TensorType) -> tf.Tensor:\n",
    "        return tf.sin(X)\n",
    "\n",
    "\n",
    "X = np.zeros((0, 1))\n",
    "Y = np.zeros((0, 1))\n",
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern12(),\n",
    "    mean_function=SineMeanFunction(),\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-15.0, max_x=15.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2fc16f84",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The above mean function does not have any trainable parameters. It is common for a mean function to have parameters that will be set during model training. To learn more about parameters see our section on [Parameters and Their Optimisation](parameters_and_their_optimisation.html)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d9c03e72",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Composition\n",
    "\n",
    "As with the kernels you can use the `+` and `*` operators to compose mean functions."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "19b7dc25",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "For example we can add a linear to our sine wave above:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "373081a6",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:47.772208Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:47.772044Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:48.135592Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:48.135093Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern12(),\n",
    "    mean_function=SineMeanFunction() + gpflow.functions.Linear(),\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-15.0, max_x=15.0)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "d70cdd09",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Or we can multiply the sine by a linear:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 10,
   "id": "f5b54f01",
   "metadata": {
    "execution": {
     "iopub.execute_input": "2022-09-07T14:39:48.137512Z",
     "iopub.status.busy": "2022-09-07T14:39:48.137349Z",
     "iopub.status.idle": "2022-09-07T14:39:48.488293Z",
     "shell.execute_reply": "2022-09-07T14:39:48.487790Z"
    }
   },
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 864x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "model = gpflow.models.GPR(\n",
    "    (X, Y),\n",
    "    kernel=gpflow.kernels.Matern12(),\n",
    "    mean_function=SineMeanFunction() * gpflow.functions.Linear(),\n",
    ")\n",
    "plot_model(model, min_x=-15.0, max_x=15.0)"
   ]
  }
 ],
